<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12119e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12119e">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12119e"> 119(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> effraie (screech owl)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Cependant, de tous les oiseaux avertisseurs de mort, il en est un, <mark>l&apos;Effraie</mark> <font color="green">[screech owl]</font>, qui est particuli&egrave;rement redout&eacute;. Il n&apos;est breton qui ne tremble jusque dans les mo&euml;lles, lorsque, dans les nuits obcures, il le voit passer en son plu-mage noir et blanc, tel un drap mortuaire, ave une croix sur le dos, rasant les maisons d&apos;un vol rapide, et qu&apos;il entend son cri d&eacute;chirant: Houek! Houek! <small> Fran&ccedil;ois Cadic, <a name="NCEL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#NCEL"><cite title="source">Nouveaux contes et l&eacute;gendes de Bretagne</cite></a> (1922) 45</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Among the Bretons, <i>Er Grekir</i> (the screech owl: the bird of the Ankou) was considered a bird of bad omen, playing a great part in predictions of death; its sharp and piercing cries are feared; if it appears on a road or in a village it brings death to it. This bird is covered with a black and white plumage, like the mortuary sheet, and it has a cross on its back. </mm> </dd></dl>
